

==> If we want to drive the car then we need to start the engine, that means car class drive() method should call engine class start() method .

Q.In how many ways car class can call engine class method ?

    1. Inheritance
    2. Composition

Note: If we use any one fo this approach then car class will become tightly coupled with engine class.That is not recommended.

##################### To develop classes with loosely coupling we need to use interface ###########################################

--> loosely coupling means without creating Object and without inheriting properties we should be able to access one class methods in another class.

--> If we make any changes in Engine class then Car class should not be effected then we can say our classes are loosely coupled.

=======
:steps: 
=======
step-1:
======

Create a interface:

IEngine.java
------------
package ashokit.in;

public interface IEngine {

	public int start();
}

Step:2
======
Now-create classes one by one

PetroEngine.java
================
package ashokit.in;

public class PetrolEngine implements IEngine {

	
	@Override
	public int start() {
		
		System.out.println("petrol engine started...");
		return 1;
	}
}

DieselEngine.java
==================
package ashokit.in;

public class DieselEngine implements IEngine {

	
	@Override
	public int start() {
		
		System.out.println("diesel engine started....");
		return 1;
	}
	
}

Car.java
=========
package ashokit.in;

public class Car {

	
	
	//we have declared a variable 
	
	private IEngine eng;
	
	//we have created a constructor to choose our user which engine need to start 
	public Car(IEngine eng) {

		this.eng=eng;
	}
	
	public void drive() {
		
		int start =  eng.start();
		
		if(start>=1) {
			
			System.out.println("Journey started");
		}else {
			
			System.out.println("Engine is in trouble ");
		}
	}
}

Main.java
--------

package ashokit.in;

public class Main {

	
	public static void main(String[] args) {

//here we pass Diesel Engine

		Car car = new Car(new DieselEngine());
		car.drive();
		
	}
}












